                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Let IGE choke on the billion plat they have.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></font id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"><br />They won't.  They'll just continue selling and selling.  Most non-powergamer players have a very hard time making 100k, much more effort is involved in doing that than in earning the $100 to buy 100k.  This is definately true for me, though I'd never spend RL money on pp.<br /><br />What'll happen if this continues badly enough, is that the bar for earning enough cash to buy decent droppable gear will rise way out of the reach of the average non-powergamer, and then the only way we'll be able to afford money like this is to buy it.  Eventually, they'll cause inflation for themselves, though the inflation in the game will be orders of magnitude worse than the rate on PP.  <br /><br />Their prices will have to go down because people won't be willing to pay enough RL money to buy the same stuff they'd have bought 6 months ago, as this stuff now costs 2x as much.  So they'll slash PP dollar rates to $75 for 100k or $50 for 100k, and inflation will just continue to go up.<br /><br />This opens a great divide in "expensive" vs "non-expensive" bazaar gear.  Expensive being used to indicate those items whose price rockets up, while non-expensive is for the rest of the items.  Which items this turns out specifically to be is largely dependant on the farmability of the items.  Low farmability items will become expensive, and high farmability items will remain fairly constant.  Because as the PP value goes down, the prices on the non-expensive items will start to go up, and as a result, these items will be farmed more, keeping the prices at a fair equilibrium.  <br /><br />The items that have reached farming saturation though will rise heavily in price, and these items will fall in to the expensive category.  If the camp that generates the items is farmed 24x7, their rate of introduction in to the game will remain constant.  These are the items that will devalue the platinum piece.  <br /><br />Unfortunately all this means that non-powergamers will reach a barrier limit, where they can't continue to upgrade their gear with any reasonable amount of effort.  I'm about there myself.  Most of the bazaar upgrades I could get would cost me 50k+, while I'm still wearing gear that I got for under 2k.  You can see the divide happening here already.  A year ago, heck, maybe 6 months ago, I'd be able to continue a steady progression of bazaar upgrades by 5 or 10k more expensive increments.  Today, there's a gap of 2500% or more between low and high end upgrades.  <br /><br />I remember when ornate pants were down to 40k on my server.  I got shoes and turban for 6k for the pair.  Now 120k is a good rate for pants, and this seems to still be going up.  I'd be lucky to pay 4k for the hat, and 25k for the shoes.</span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
