                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> Even prior to me speaking with Yantis, I never had any issues with people selling virtual assets.  The time investment that is required to attain many of the great things in EQ is outlandish.  Many people spend so much time at work that they are unable to camp for 30 straight hours for certain items.  They do however have the additional funds to purchase it.<br /><br />Example<br />I work sometimes 90 - 100 hour weeks.  You can bet your sweet arse I did not have time to sleep let alone log into the game.   While I am working, most of my friends are progressing through levels, AA, and gaining equipment.  I want to keep up with them so we can still group, so I buy some equipment/plat to allow me to progress a little faster.  All I have done is basically outsource someone who has far too much time on their hands to get the item for me.  It is the same thing you do in the bazaar everyday.<br /><br />Would I have gained the uber staff of insta-justice on my own?  Possibly, but for the sacrifice of a few bucks I have just increased by enjoyment in the game.<br /><br />When most people buy the items, they are merely attempting to maximize their fun in game.  They are basically hiring someone at a low rate to log in and do the 40 hour camp for them, because either they are impatient or literally do not have the time to do it.  A lot of people are against selling in game assets.  <br />A lot of people enjoy grinding out those camps, attaining all their levels, and fighting it through.  Those types of people like to start a business and oversee it's operations until they are rich.<br /><br />Then there are those that like to buy items/plat.  These are the types of people that like to invest in a company and get a sizable return with little amounts of effort.  All they have to do is have the cash on hand and the desire to profit.  <br /><br />Even without MSS/IGE people would take advantage of the situation.  Those organizations may give an easy access into online commerce but even back in the old bbs MUD days people were selling accounts.  That was before the internet, before paypal, and before precious precious broadband.<br /><br />I appreciate everyone's views on this subject.  I also find it terribly amusing how much revenue people can make by selling Online Virtual assets.  The industry is a multi-million dollar a year gig and they are do nothing but playing middle man.  <br /><br />They are doing exactly what companies like Allakhazam do.  Allakhzam allows people to volunteer game information then turns around and charges a subscription to view it.  It is free information, the information in itself is a virtual asset.  I have more problems with companies charging ridiculous subscription fees to view volunteered content than someone selling something they worked hard for.<br /><br /><br /></span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
